1. Introduction¶

Title: Underlying Trends from Spotify Top 200 Chart¶

Description of the Original Dataset¶

(https://www.kaggle.com/sashankpillai/spotify-top-200-charts-20202021)

The dataset include all the songs that have been on the Top 200 Weekly (Global) charts of Spotify in 2020 & 2021.

The dataset include the following features:

  • Highest Charting Position: The highest position that the song has been on in the Spotify Top 200 Weekly Global Charts in 2020 & 2021.

  • Number of Times Charted: The number of times that the song has been on in the Spotify Top 200 Weekly Global Charts in 2020 & 2021.

  • Week of Highest Charting: The week when the song had the Highest Position in the Spotify Top 200 Weekly Global Charts in 2020 & 2021.

  • Song Name: Name of the song that has been on in the Spotify Top 200 Weekly Global Charts in 2020 & 2021.

  • Song iD: The song ID provided by Spotify (unique to each song).

  • Streams: Approximate number of streams the song has.

  • Artist: The main artist/ artists involved in making the song.

  • Artist Followers: The number of followers the main artist has on Spotify.

  • Genre: The genres the song belongs to.

  • Release Date: The initial date that the song was released.

  • Weeks Charted: The weeks that the song has been on in the Spotify Top 200 Weekly Global Charts in 2020 & 2021.

  • Popularity:The popularity of the track. The value will be between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular.

  • Danceability: Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable.

  • Acousticness: A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic.

  • Energy: Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy.

  • Instrumentalness: Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content.

  • Liveness: Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live.

  • Loudness: The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track. Values typical range between -60 and 0 db.

  • Speechiness: Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value.

  • Tempo: The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). In musical terminology, tempo is the speed or pace of a given piece and derives directly from the average beat duration.

  • Valence: A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).

  • Chord: The main chord of the song instrumental.

*Acknowledgements*

This dataset would not be possible without the help of spotifycharts.com and Spotipy Python Library

There are total unique values of 1556.

Description of the Sampled Dataset¶

Spotify Dataset (spotify_top_200_sample.csv)

  • This is a random sample of song attributes for songs that have been on the Top 200 Weekly Global charts of Spotify in the years 2020 and 2021.

Motivation¶

  • From the Spotify Top 200 songs chart, we would like to figure out whether there is interesting underlying trends between various attributes given in the dataset.

Research Questions¶

  1. What would be a relationship between a song's 'Energy' and the number of 'Streams'? Moreover, would there be any additional significant association between these two variables when grouping by four different 'seasons'?

  2. Is there a difference of a song's tempo by different seasons (Specifically between summer and fall)?

  3. Is there a linear relationship between a song's highest chart ranking and the song's artist features in the sample?

  4. Can we detect any noticeable association between 'hip hop' or 'rap' songs and their music components? Plus, can we accurately predict whether a song is hip hop or not based on its music components?

Since we do not have a column 'seasons' in the dataset yet, we have to add the column. Below is the code of adding 'Seasons' column.

(Spring: Mar/Apr/May, Summer: Jun/Jul/Aug, Fall: Sep/Oct/Nov, Winter: Dec/Jan/Feb)

In [13]:
df['seasons'] = ""

for i in range(len(df)):
    if (df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '3')|(df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '4')|(df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '5'):
        df['seasons'].iloc[i] = 'spring'
    elif (df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '6')|(df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '7')|(df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '8'):
        df['seasons'].iloc[i] = 'summer'
    elif (df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '9')|(df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '10')|(df['Release_Date_month'].iloc[i] == '11'):
        df['seasons'].iloc[i] = 'fall'
    else:
        df['seasons'].iloc[i] = 'winter'

By categorizing songs by four different seasons, it is interesting that only fall season songs seem to show a negative correlation between 'Energy' and 'Streams', indicating that songs released in fall with lower energy tend to be favored more by people.

3. Inference¶

Research Question¶

Is there a difference of a song's tempo by different seasons (Specifically between summer and fall)?

Hypothesis¶

  • $H_0: \mu_{Summer} = \mu_{Fall}$
  • $H_A: \mu_{Summer} \neq \mu_{Fall}$

Condition Check¶

  1. Random Sample

Since we can find out from our dataset's description, "This is a random sample of song attributes for songs that have been on the Top 200 Weekly Global charts of Spotify in the years 2020 and 2021.", our samples would also be randomly sampled. Thus, this condition is met.

  1. $n_1 <$ (10% of the population 1 size), $n_2 < $ (10% of the population 2 size)
In [18]:
len(df[df['seasons'] == 'summer'])
Out[18]:
129
In [19]:
len(df[df['seasons'] == 'fall'])
Out[19]:
101

The sizes of population 1 (songs released in the summer) and 2 (songs released in the fall) should be at least 1290 and 1010 in order to satisfy the condition. Considering that the overall population size of the dataset is 1556 (check the *acknowledgements* in the introduction), this does not make sense, thus violating the condition.

  1. Either...
  • $n_1 > 30$, $n_2 > 30$

or

  • the population 1 and 2's distributions are normal.

Both the sample sizes are larger than 30, hence this condition is satisfied.

We can see that the second condition is not met. Theoretically, we cannot conduct the hypothesis test, but we will do the test with caution.

Since we do not know the populations' standard deviations ($\sigma_1, \sigma_2$), we instead use the samples' standard deviations ($s_1, s_2$) and use the t-distribution as well.

In [20]:
n_summer = len(df[df['seasons'] == 'summer'])
n_fall = len(df[df['seasons'] == 'fall'])

tempo_summer = df[df['seasons'] == 'summer']['Tempo'].mean()
tempo_fall = df[df['seasons'] == 'fall']['Tempo'].mean()

std_summer = df[df['seasons'] == 'summer']['Tempo'].std()
std_fall = df[df['seasons'] == 'fall']['Tempo'].std()
In [21]:
point_est = tempo_summer - tempo_fall
se = ((std_summer**2)/n_summer + (std_fall**2)/n_fall)**0.5

from scipy.stats import t

test_stat = (point_est - 0) / se

p_val = 2 * (1 - t.cdf(abs(test_stat), df = min(n_summer, n_fall)))
p_val
Out[21]:
0.19676903892652442

Since the p-value is about 0.20, which is relatively larger than the typical significance level $\alpha = 0.05$, we would fail to reject the null and conclude that there is no average tempo difference of songs by seasons.

  • $H_0: \beta_{Number\ of\ Times\ Charted} = \beta_{Streams} = \beta_{Artist\ Followers} = \beta_{Popularity} = 0$
  • $H_A$: At least one of the slopes is not zero.

Since the p-value for the F-test is 1.15e-63, which is significantly smaller than the significance level, $\alpha = 0.05$, we reject the null and conclude that at least one of the slopes in the corresponding population model is not zero.

To sum up, we found out that there would be at least some linear relationship between a song's highest charting position and its song's artist features. Instead of running multiple test models one at a time, we made a for loop to iterate faster.

In [49]:
pred_list = ['Danceability', 'Energy', 'Loudness', 'Speechiness', 'Acousticness', 'Liveness', 'Tempo', 'Duration_ms', 'Valence']
elim_list = []
full_mod = smf.logit('y_hiphop ~ Danceability + Energy + Loudness + Speechiness + Acousticness + Liveness + Tempo + Duration_ms + Valence', data = df_train).fit()

for pred in pred_list:
    print("Model Without %s"%(pred))
    
    # Every time the loop iterates, the test mod is going to run the logistic regression function dropping one predictor from 'predictor list'
    test_mod = smf.logit('y_hiphop ~ Danceability + Energy + Loudness + Speechiness + Acousticness + Liveness + Tempo + Duration_ms + Valence - %s'%(pred), data = df_train).fit()
    
    print("AIC Score of Full Model: %s"%(full_mod.aic))
    print("AIC Score of Test Model: %s"%(test_mod.aic))
    
    if full_mod.aic < test_mod.aic:
        print("Full Model is Better")
    else:
        print("Test Model is Better")
        
        # Append the test mod's AIC score and its model's dropped predictor
        elim_list.append(str(test_mod.aic) + "Without %s"%(pred))
    print('-----------------------------------')

# If there is at least one element in the list, pick the element with the minimum value
if len(elim_list) != 0:
    print("Final Model Selection")
    print(min(elim_list))

# When there is no value in the elimination list (Meaning that none of the test models have lower AIC scores than the full model's AIC score)
else:
    print("Full Model is the Best, Stop Backward Iteration!")

Hypothesis Test (Reduced (Final) vs Full)¶

  • $H_0$: The reduced model is better than the full model. ($\beta_{Duration\ ms} = \beta_{Energy} = \beta_{Tempo} = 0$)
  • $H_A$: The reduced model is incorrect because at least one of the slopes that we dropped is not zero.

Test Statistic & p-value¶

In [55]:
# Log-Likelihood Ratio Test
test_stat = -2*(final_mod.llf - full_mod.llf)
test_stat
Out[55]:
1.6627923135308151
In [56]:
from scipy.stats import chi2

p_val = 1 - chi2.cdf(test_stat, df = 3)
p_val
Out[56]:
0.6452373459230079

Since the p-value is relatively larger than the typical significance level $\alpha = 0.05$, we fail to reject the null and conclude that the reduced model is better than the full model.

Equation of the Final Model¶

$\log(\frac{\hat p_{Hiphop}}{1 - \hat p_{Hiphop}}) = -4.3158 + 4.0778x_{Danceability} - 0.1279x_{Loudness} + 7.9076x_{Speechiness} - 1.0820x_{Acousticness} + 2.1592x_{Liveness} - 2.8531x_{Valence}$

Although the final model has the lowest AIC score compared to other test models, we can see from the summary above that there are still some explanatory variables with high p-values ('Loudness', 'Acousticness'). This might indicate that the final model may not be the most parsimonious model.

We may try dropping these two variables, fitting a new reduced model and comparing its AIC score with the final model.

However, even if we have a result that the new reduced model is better, its AIC score is surely higher than the final model's AIC score. Thus, we cannot say that the new reduced model is the most parsimonious model.

Predictive Probability Thresholds Selection¶

In [69]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def tpr_fpr_thresh(y, pred_prob, thresh):
    yhat = 1*(pred_prob >= thresh)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true=y, y_pred=yhat).ravel()
    tpr = tp / (fn + tp)
    fpr = fp / (fp + tn)
    return pd.DataFrame({'threshold':[thresh],
                         'tpr':[tpr], 
                         'fpr':[fpr]})

Tying with our research questions, we may think of a scenario such as:

Suppose we are working as data scientists at Spotify. Many different music awards shows are held every year, and songs are nominated and awarded from different genres. We would like to evaluate whether a song in the Spotify Top 200 chart can be considered as hip hop or not and create a nomination list of hip hop songs based on the classification that we made. However, we would be penalized when labeling a song's genre incorrectly. Considering our goal is to have a possibility of mislabeling as low as possible, we should therefore focus more of having lower false positive rate rather than higher true positive rate.

Comparing all threshold values above, the threshold of $p_0 = 0.4$ seems to have the most reasonable and best trade-off between false and true positive rate.

(False Positive Rate = 0.123, True Positive Rate = 0.66)

6. Conclusion¶

Throughout the diverse analyses above, we have found some interesting results:

  • People tend to prefer more of listening to songs with lower energy (relatively 'soft' or 'quiet' songs) in the fall whereas more energetic songs are favored by people in the other three seasons.

  • While it may be easy to think that a song with lower energy might be slower (tempo), there is no difference of a song's tempo that was released in the summer and fall on average.

  • Except that the linear regression conditions are not met, it is significant that a song's artist features (Number of Times Charted, Followers, Streams, Popularity) do affect the song's highest charting position.

  • Assuming the music components (explanatory variables) in the logistic model to have about the same values, we would expect 'Danceability' and 'Speechiness' to be the most influential variables when it comes to determining whether a song is hip hop or not due to large slope coefficients.

Since there are several columns that are related to time and date (ex. 'Released_Date_month', 'Weeks_Charted_day'), we could do more deep analysis related to 'Time Series' although we have not learned yet. For instance, we may inquire 'Are there any detectable trends in this dataset that might reflect some significant events happened in 2020 and 2021?'
